  {
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "One thing missing from the guide and I wanted to achieve is to easily handle the case of already existing querystring parameters.\r\n\r\nFor example let's say I load https://website.com/?loggedIn=1 and I want to use the routing feature. What I'd like to do is:\r\n\r\n```js\r\nconst search = instantsearch({\r\n  // ... appId, apiKey...\r\n  routing: {\r\n    stateMapping: {\r\n      stateToRoute(uiState) {\r\n        return {\r\n          loggedIn: window.isUserLoggedIn,\r\n          q: uiState.query\r\n        };\r\n      },\r\n      routeToState(routeState) {\r\n        return {\r\n          query: routeState.q\r\n        };\r\n      }\r\n    }\r\n  }\r\n});\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis ^ works and will add loggedIn query parameter to the url. But what if window.isUserLoggedIn state changes from the outside (user logs out, it's an ajax call)? I would like to turn the url to: `https://website.com/?loggedIn=0&q=phone`.\r\n\r\nTo do so for now I guess I would have to create my own router or own widget?\r\n\r\nWhat I may want as a user:\r\n\r\n```js\r\nconst search = instantsearch(...);\r\nsearch.router.write(); // triggers write on the history router\r\n```\r\n\r\nThere are implications to this so I just want to have your opinion on the proposal.",
